title: For Sale:  Remington 5r Mil Spec 308
postcontent:
Model 700 Stainless R5 Mil-Spec

This is a great rifle and personal favorite of the local long range 308 crowd.

Features a M700 stainless steel barreled action with a 24 inch R5 mil-spec barrel, the same barrel used in the M-24 sniper rifles. Varmint barrel with 11.25 inch twist rate with five lands and grooves and eleven degree target crown. Stock has aluminum bedding in block in standard VS configuration.

"Offering this Model 700 for ten years is a testimony to the popularity and acceptance by shooters wanting to own an exceptionally accurate rifle at a reasonable price," states Category Manager, Dave Regula. At the core of the 700 with 5-R Rifling is the machined stainless steel, cylindrical Model 700 receiver design ensuring uniformity, strength and solid bedding area. Unique to this precision rifle is the 24-inch stainless steel, heavy barrel featuring 5-R Tactical Rifling -- the same hammer-forged barrel used on the M-24 sniper rifles.

 The 5-R Rifling barrel features five lands with a right hand twist which allows for less bearing surface on the bullet for slightly increased velocity.

As a result of less bullet drag, copper fouling in the bore is reduced ensuring long-term accuracy and consistency. The barrel is offered with a 110 target-style crown and a 1 in 11.25-inch twist.

The rock-solid barreled action is full-length, aluminum bedded into a well-designed H-S Precision stock for enhanced stability and shot-to-shot consistency. Add Remington's X-Mark ProÂ® externally adjustable trigger, designed to "break-like-glass" and set at 3.5 pounds from the factory, and this rifle delivers surgical-like accuracy.

This rifle has been threaded for a suppressor or muzzle break and has a thread protector.  Does Not come with the scope or rings, but does come with the stainless 20MOA scope rail. Trigger has been tuned. This is the most accurate rifle I've ever fired. It will shoot any ammo I've fed it, into little bitty groups.  Will sell for $950 or would take cash plus a lighter weight 308. This one is heavier than my wife can handle.

Possibly a 270 or 30-06 plus cash.

title: For Sale:  NIB FNH Five-seveN MKII 5.7x28mm Pistol FN 20rd
postcontent: You are bidding on a Factory New FNH USA Five-seveNÂ® MKII Pistol chambered in 5.7x28mm. The 5.7x28mm cartridge was designed as a lightweight and reduced size cartridge with the performance of a rifle round. The .224 diameter bullet and comparatively small casing are what allows both the FN P90 and the Five-seveNÂ® pistol to hold so many rounds. The standard magazine capacity for this pistol is 20 rounds, with higher and lower capacity magazines being offered. The 5.7mm cartridge was designed to perform optimally out of a shorter barrel and generates velocities so high that several loadings are available that are classified as armor piercing. For these reasons the 5.7mm cartridge faithfully serves the US Secret Service in protecting some of our nations most influential people. While the Five-seveNÂ® is available in several different configurations the model that you are bidding on has adjustable sights that can be adjusted for both windage and elevation. Only serious buyers should make a contact not scams, thanks.

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson Hand Ejector - 2nd model - .455 to .45acp
location: Boca Raton, Palm Beach, South Florida
postcontent:
Up for sale is a S&W large frame revolver manufactured for the Canadian military in 1916. Due to a shortage of the British Webleys during WW1, Smith and Wesson was awarded  contracts to manufacture these for both the British and Canadian governments. They were chambered for the British .455 rimmed revolver round wihich had a 260 grain lead bullet and were finished with a high gloss commercial bluing. This excellent example appears to be an unissued one which was later returned to the US and rechambered for our .45 acp round. This was accomplished by milling the frame slightly so the .45 acp could be loaded onto full moonclips being that it had a rimless type casing. This one is in excellent condition with a nice bore, positive lockup and precise timing. Still retains the lanyard ring and sports later style wood grips. Included are three full moonclips and 20 rounds of .454 cal. ammo loaded close to the original chambering with a 255 grain lead bullet. 750.00 or best reasonable offer. FTF transaction only. Must be 21 and have a Florida ID or FFL to purchase. C&R is okay for this one. Only trade considered would be for a Fender Deluxe Reverb amplifier (either a vintage in good condition or a '65 reissue in excellet condition).

title: For Sale:  FS: Japanese 6.5  Carcano Type I Rifle
postcontent: The Type I rifle was produced by Italy for the Japanese Empire prior to World War II. After the invasion of China, all Arisaka production was required for use of the Imperial Army, so under the terms of the Anti-Comintern Pact, the Imperial Navy contracted with Italy for this weapon in 1937. The Type I is based on the Type 38 rifle and utilizes a Carcano action, but retains the Arisaka/Mauser type 5-round box magazine. The Type I was utilized primarily by Japanese Imperial Naval Forces. It is chambered for the 6.5 x 50 mm cartridge. Approximately 120,000 Type I rifles were produced by Italian arsenals for Japan between 1937 through 1939.bore is in decent shape,wood has normal war wear. missing cleaning rod.everything is there besides the cleaning rod. Nice overall rifle. $25.00 shipping to your FFL dealer. email me for further photo's of rifle.

postcontent:
Anderson Manufacturing forged lower receiver with integrated trigger guard. Hard coat anodized black. Mil-spec (not commercial) buffer tube, with chrome silicon buffer spring for longer spring life without metal fatigue. Safariland Accu-Wedge also goes with it.

DPMS lower parts kit for durability and reliability.

The front sight post has been replaced with a Tru-Glo fiber optic sight for better visibility, and includes both green and orange light tubes, adjustment tool and replacement tool.

PSA Forged 7075-T6 A3 AR upper is hard coat anodized black for durability. Featuring M4 feedramp cuts and T-marks on the rail.

I built this rifle with the intention of keeping it, but another project is taking priority. I have cycled about 10 rounds through this gun, just to check feed and function. It ran flawlessly.

title: For Sale:  New Mossberg 590 A1 Sidewinder - 10 shot rotary magazine - MUST SEE
postcontent:
This beast started with a new Mossberg 590 A1 12-gauge shotgun. If you're not familiar with this model, it is the beefed-up LEO/MIL version of the Mossberg 500 series. Where the standard 500 has a polymer trigger guard and safety, this one is all metal. It also has a heavy duty barrel to withstand severe duty usage. 

That in itself is a great shotgun - but then Adaptive Tactical makes their Sidewinder Venom kit for this gun. It converts the regular feed tube to a welded box magazine that accepts quick change rotary drums, 10 rounds at a time. Put it all together, and you have one of the most amazing shotguns that has been seen since the days of the original Street Sweeper.

Adaptive Tactical's adjustable M4-style stock and fore grip complete the gun. I also added a Midwest Industries heavy duty QD swivel to the stock for single point carry.

This gun is in new condition, and the conversion was performed by a professional gunsmith. It has (3) 10-round drum magazines; two of them are still in their factory packaging. The drums by themselves sell for over $100 each when you can find them. Includes the factory Mossberg box if you want it as well as the parts changed out in the conversion.

$700 FIRM takes it home.

I'm not looking for trades; selling only to complete a project. If you can find it cheaper somewhere else (because you will not), go buy it. Dealer cost on the components alone is more than my price. Lowball offers will simply be ignored. This is NOT a cheap Maverick 88 that has been converted; it is Mossberg's top of the line in the 500 series.

Can meet in Georgetown area, will sell ONLY to KY resident - NO EXCEPTIONS. Valid KY driver's license required; valid KY CCDW license preferred. Due to "no-show" buyers, I won't travel outside the Georgetown area. Bill of sale given at time of purchase.

postcontent: I am soon to retire and relocating and selling all my gun collection that I have accumulated over the years, this ammo is among the last and best of my 50+ year collection and it is truly museum/collector grade in light of the exceptionally well preserved condition of the ammunition, original shipping crate, packaging, manufacturer, and historical context. The 10 cardboard boxes of 25 rds each have Oriental characters printed on them. I bought this ammo in 1987 in a factory sealed spam can of 450 rds and fired 15 rds for a function check; every round fired properly, like it was made yesterday. I then put the crate in my climatically controlled vault and it has sat there untouched since 1987 until I took it out today to take these pics. This original wooden shipping crate contains 250 rds in unopend sealed boxes (except the one box I opened to photograph)and 185 rds on stripper clips, for a total of 435 rds. This is cleanest, finest ammo for its age I have ever seen. If you are interested in this ammo, you are probably a collector and know more about it than I do, but you can see the headstamp in one of the pics and I think it was made in 1951 by the Chinese, probably for use against us in Korea. There are plenty of 6.5 Jap Arisaka rifles out there but very little ammo for them, my price for this ammo is less than any other I have found and this is the real deal ammo in the original factory crate and packaging. I would prefer to sell this locally so I don't have to go thru the hassle and expense of shipping it.
